{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6e45f813-cf1f-4210-aa20-beba6c174028","content":"Use `dotnet watch` to automatically re-run tests on every file save:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nThis watches for changes, rebuilds, and re-runs just that one test. The `--filter` flag keeps the feedback loop tight by running only the failing test.\n\n**Your bug:** `RemoveStock` subtracts without checking if enough stock exists. It needs to throw when `quantity > available`. Fix that in `InventoryService.RemoveStock`, save the file, and `dotnet watch` will automatically re-run the test.\n\nWant me to fix the bug as well?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3251e342-40c3-4786-85cd-2264b1209253","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for the test project. Since they're using .NET 10 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as configured in global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test` to get hot reload for tests.\n\nLet me check what's available. With .NET 10 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet test --hotreload` is actually a new feature. But the more established approach is `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me suggest using `dotnet watch test` which will watch for file changes and re-run tests automatically. This is the standard approach for rapid iteration.\n\n\nActually, with .NET 10 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet test --hotreload` is the better option—it keeps the test host running and applies changes via hot reload without a full rebuild, which is more efficient than restarting the entire test process.","outputTokens":371,"requestId":"4817:4804C:8D6EC1:A2EA1E:69FBED38"},"id":"894eaaa3-6713-4bf7-a62f-a44a97ba864b","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:39:14.394Z","parentId":"3ba52abf-b6f8-4816-a0e0-abb32dd5dad7"}
